5","before 1302":"vóór 1302","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1264":"1264","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England"},"en":{"1264–":"1264–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1284–1335":"1284–1335","1264–Female":"1264–Deceased","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","before 1302":"before 1302","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1264":"1264","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Veurne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Henri, Mimose.","French and Italian (Piedmont): topographic name for someone who lived near a grove of alders, from Old French <i>verne</i> ‘alder tree’, a word of Gaulish origin. Compare   Laverne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vernier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Emile, Jean Michel, Lucien.","French:","topographic name for someone who lived near an alder tree (see   Verne   1)."]},{"name":"Varnado","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alban, Alphonse, Andre, Celestine, Monique, Patrice.","Altered form of French <b>Vernadeau</b>: cognate of <b>Vernade</b>, a habitational name from La Vernade, the name of several places in the central part of France, derived from Old French <i>verne</i> ‘alder tree’ (see   Verne  ). The surname <i>Vernadeau</i> is no longer found in France."]},{"name":"Laverne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel.","French: variant of   Lavergne   and   Verne   ‘alder tree’, with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":26,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":51,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":64,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":73,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":118,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Van Veurne was born in 1264, in Yorkshire, England. She married John Richmond before 1302, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1264–":"1264–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1284–1335":"1284–1335","1264–Female":"1264–Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","before 1302":"enne 1302","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1264":"1264","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1264–":"1264–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1284–1335":"1284–1335","1264–Female":"1264–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","before 1302":"ennen vuotta 1302","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1264":"1264","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1264–":"1264–Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1284–1335":"1284–1335","1264–Female":"1264–Décédée","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","before 1302":"avant 1302","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1264":"1264","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Van Veurne est née en 1264, à Everwyck, Angleterre. Elle a épousé John Richmond avant 1302, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1264–":"1264–Verstorben","–Male":"Verstorben","1284–1335":"1284–1335","1264–Female":"1264–Verstorben","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","before 1302":"vor 1302","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1264":"1264","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","lifeSummary":"Van Veurne wurde 1264 in Yorkshire, England geboren. Sie hat vor 1302 in England John Richmond geheiratet. Sie hatten mindes